    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-07-09T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-07-09T16:00:00-05:00" n="595"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d595">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">815.00 Revolutions/210: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lay</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="12" xml:id="d595fn12">The same on the same date to the
                        Minister in Nicaragua as Department’s No. 152.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-07-09T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 9, 1931—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>57. Commander Special Service Squadron reports that conditions on east coast
                    Nicaragua and north coast Honduras are entirely tranquil <pb facs="0703" n="583"
                        xml:id="pg_583"/> and therefore recommends withdrawal of the only remaining
                    United States war vessel, the <hi rend="italic">Sacramento</hi>, from those
                    regions.</p>
                <p>Please telegraph your views to the Department.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
